Pre-Game Insights: Australia looks set to welcome back Travis Head from injury while the Netherlands need some runs from their top-order.
Scott Edwards, the Netherlands captain, is an Australian citizen and has introduced a Netherlands team song that is a rebrand of the song of his favorite Australian Football League club Richmond.
Australia and Netherlands have only met twice in ODI cricket, both at World Cups in 2003 and 2007, with Australia winning both matches.
Australia's new-ball bowlers have not taken a powerplay wicket in the last three games, and Delhi has been an excellent batting strip.
Steven Smith is averaging just 23.22 in ODIs this year from nine innings, including three ducks, and striking at just 81.64.
Netherlands' top two have struggled, with Max O'Dowd making just 55 runs in four innings at a strike-rate of just 57.89.
The Netherlands need some runs from their openers if they are to put pressure on Australia.
Travis Head is back with the Australia squad and is set to open alongside David Warner if he plays.
Mitchell Starc needs two wickets to go past Lasith Malinga (56) to third all-time on the ODI World Cup wicket-takers list.
Australia are the only team to have gone wicketless three times in the first powerplay in this World Cup.
